Magic Professions of the Golden Age (Lost)
During the Golden Age of Magic (10,000 – 9,000 B.S.), magic was not divided into rigid single schools as it is today. The greatest practitioners were polymaths who wove together multiple arcane disciplines into seamless masterpieces. These elite professions shaped entire civilizations. Their knowledge was largely lost after the Shattering, surviving only in fragmented scrolls, ruined artifacts, and half-understood legends.
Below is a detailed overview of the requested professions.
Artificery (The Art of Living Craft)
Role in the Golden Age:
Artificers were master enchanters and magical craftsmen who created everyday wonders and legendary artifacts alike. They forged weapons that sang, armor that healed wounds, and tools that bent probability. Flying ships, self-repairing cities, and ever-flowing fountains were all products of high artificery.
Magic Schools Combined:

Rune / Inscription Magic (core) — Permanent enchantments on objects and materials.
Aetherforge Magic (dwarven specialty) — Merging raw Aetherite crystals with spells.
Transmutation — Altering the physical properties of base materials.
Soul Magic (light touch) — Binding minor spirits or intent into items.
Elemental Schools — Infusing fire, lightning, or nature aspects.

Surface Analysis Today:
Modern “artificers” are little more than advanced blacksmiths or jewelers who create minor enchanted items (glowing swords, slightly sharper axes) using basic elemental infusion. True permanent, intelligent, or self-powering artifacts are extremely rare and usually looted from ruins. The loss of Rune Magic and Aetherforge means most modern enchantments fade after decades instead of lasting millennia.
Golem and Automaton Construction
Role in the Golden Age:
These masters built loyal servants, tireless laborers, and unstoppable war machines. From small household golems that swept floors to continent-spanning guardian colossi and thinking crystal automata capable of independent thought, they powered the Golden Age economy and military.
Magic Schools Combined:

Conjuration — Summoning and binding raw elemental or spiritual matter.
Transmutation — Shaping stone, metal, crystal, or clay into functional bodies.
Rune / Inscription Magic — Engraving command matrices and power circuits.
Aetherforge Magic — Creating power cores from Aetherite.
Soul Magic — Granting limited intelligence or true sentience (highly regulated).
Abjuration — Protective wards to prevent rampancy or external control.

Surface Analysis Today:
Only the most basic stone or iron golems can still be created, and they require constant maintenance by teams of mages. Most are mindless and follow very simple commands. Ancient automata found in ruins are highly prized (and feared) — some still function after 9,000 years, leading to legends of “cursed guardians.” The art of creating truly intelligent constructs is completely lost.
Astral Architects
Role in the Golden Age:
The most awe-inspiring profession. Astral Architects designed and built floating cities, sky palaces, ley-line highways, and extradimensional pocket realms. They shaped the very geography of magic across Aetheria.
Magic Schools Combined:

Gravity / Stellar Magic — Levitation, orbital manipulation, and structural integrity in the air.
Conjuration & Abjuration — Creating stable extradimensional spaces and protective barriers.
Aetherforge & Rune Magic — Building self-sustaining power frameworks.
Void Magic (advanced) — Tearing and stabilizing portals to anchor floating structures.
Transmutation — Reshaping massive amounts of stone and crystal mid-air.

Surface Analysis Today:
Many ruined floating citadels still drift across the skies, some inhabited by outcasts or monsters. Modern mages can barely create small hovering platforms or floating lanterns. The few attempts to rebuild sky structures in the last centuries have ended in catastrophic crashes. Astral Architect knowledge is among the most sought-after lost arts.
Soul Forgers
Role in the Golden Age:
Feared and respected, Soul Forgers worked directly with the essence of life and death. They created soul-bound weapons, performed true resurrections, crafted phylacteries, transferred consciousness into new bodies, and forged powerful artificial souls for elite golems or vessels.
Magic Schools Combined:

Soul Magic (primary) — Binding, shaping, reading, and transferring souls.
Necromancy / Death Magic — Handling the boundary between life and death.
Blood Magic — Using life-force as fuel or anchor.
Rune & Inscription Magic — Permanent soul-binding sigils.
Emotion & Dream Magic — Shaping personality and memory during forging.

Surface Analysis Today:
Completely outlawed or lost in most societies. Modern necromancers can only raise mindless undead. True soul work is considered the highest blasphemy in human kingdoms and carries an automatic death sentence. Rumors persist of secret Soul Forger cults operating in demonic territories or hidden dwarven deep holds. Ancient soul-forged artifacts (especially sentient weapons) still surface occasionally and are incredibly dangerous.
Chronomancers
Role in the Golden Age:
The rarest and most tightly regulated profession. Chronomancers manipulated the flow of time itself — accelerating growth of crops, slowing aging for the elite, creating limited time loops for study or combat, and performing dangerous historical divinations.
Magic Schools Combined:

Time Magic (core, extremely rare aptitude) — Acceleration, deceleration, and limited loops.
Divination — Viewing possible futures and past echoes.
Soul Magic — Protecting the caster’s mind/soul from temporal paradoxes.
Abjuration — Creating stable time bubbles.
Dream Magic — Entering “time outside of time” through dream states.

Surface Analysis Today:
No known true Chronomancers exist. The few mages who show minor time-related talents can only slightly slow their own aging or accelerate the ripening of fruit. Ancient time-related ruins (places where time flows strangely) are considered extremely hazardous. Many scholars believe the Shattering itself was partially caused by reckless Chronomancy experiments.
Void Singers
Role in the Golden Age:
Mystical poet-mages who sang reality into new shapes. They opened stable gates between planes, summoned entities from beyond, tore temporary holes in existence for teleportation, and created “void architecture” (pockets of non-space). Their songs could drive armies mad or calm raging mana storms.
Magic Schools Combined:

Void Magic (primary) — Reality tearing, phasing, and extra-dimensional manipulation.
Music / Bardic Magic — Using sound and vibration as the focusing medium.
Conjuration & Teleportation — Safe summoning and travel.
Emotion Magic — Weaving feelings into songs to affect reality.
Abjuration — Containing the destructive forces they unleashed.

Surface Analysis Today:
Modern bards can produce minor emotional or physical effects with music, but nothing on the scale of true Void Singing. Surviving Void Singer ruins are among the most dangerous places in Aetheria — locations where gravity fails, reality frays, or things that should not exist still linger. Some hedge mages claim to have heard fragments of the old songs in ancient sites, but attempting to replicate them usually ends in disappearance or madness.

These professions represent the height of what was possible when magic was abundant and multiple aptitudes could be mastered by singular geniuses or when a few worked together. Today, even the most talented mage is lucky to command one school at a basic level. The rediscovery of even fragments of these lost arts could dramatically shift the balance of power in the current age.
